%N A390118 Least positive integer m such that m*n + 1 = p^2 for some prime number p.
%C A390118 a(n) always exists since there are (infinitely many) primes p congruent to 1 modulo n.
%C A390118 Conjecture: a(n) <= (n+5)*(n-1) for all n > 1 (verified for n <= 12000).
%H A390118 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A390118/b390118.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..4000</a>
%e A390118 a(1) = 3 since 3*1 + 1 = 2^2 and 2 is prime.
%e A390118 a(2) = 4 since 4*2 + 1 = 3^2 and 3 is prime.
%e A390118 a(13) = 216 = (13+5)*(13-1) since 216*13 + 1 = 53^2 and 53 is prime.
%t A390118 PQ[n_]:=PQ[n]=PrimeQ[Sqrt[n]];
%t A390118 tab={};Do[m=1;Label[bb];If[PQ[m*n+1],tab=Append[tab,m];Goto[aa]];
%t A390118 m=m+1;Goto[bb];Label[aa],{n,1,70}];Print[tab]
%o A390118 (PARI) a(n) = my(m=1); while (isprimepower(m*n+1) != 2, m++); m; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Nov 02 2025
%o A390118 (Python)
%o A390118 from math import isqrt
%o A390118 from sympy import isprime
%o A390118 from itertools import count
%o A390118 def a(n): return next(m for m in count(1) if (p:=isqrt(q:=m*n+1))**2==q and isprime(p))
%o A390118 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 71)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Nov 02 2025
